Note:
==============================================================================
Date - Proleptic Gregorian Calendar Date
==============================================================================

A Date represents a calendar date as a (year, month, day) triple in the
proleptic Gregorian calendar - i.e. the Gregorian rules extended
backward past the 1582 reform. This is the calendar implied by ISO
8601 §3.2.1.

Year range: a signed 64-bit ordinal-day counter covers approximately
+/- 25 billion years from the Gregorian epoch (0001-01-01), placing it
well beyond any conceivable civil-date arithmetic horizon.

Internal representation: a single Integer holding the count of days
since 0000-03-01 (Howard Hinnant's "rata die from March" convention).
March-relative numbering removes the leap-day discontinuity from the
month-arithmetic kernel: every "year" runs from March through the
following February so the leap day is always the last day. The
public year/month/day accessors translate to the conventional
January-start year on read.

Algorithms used:
  - Hinnant, H. "chrono-Compatible Low-Level Date Algorithms",
    2013 (canonical reference for civil_from_days, days_from_civil,
    weekday_from_days, days_from_civil_ordinal). Proven correct over
    the full int64 range.
  - ISO 8601:2019 §3.4 (week date format, week-of-year computation).
  - Gregorian rules per Pope Gregory XIII, Inter Gravissimas (1582):
    leap year iff (divisible by 4 AND not divisible by 100) OR
    divisible by 400.

References:
  ISO 8601-1:2019 (Date and time -- Representations for information
       interchange)
  RFC 3339 §5.6 (date format ABNF)
  Hinnant 2013 (http://howardhinnant.github.io/date_algorithms.html)
  Reingold & Dershowitz, "Calendrical Calculations" (4th ed., 2018)
==============================================================================
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as MemoryCore

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Layout constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant DATE_SIZE_BYTES as Integer is 8
Constant DATE_OFFSET as Integer is 0

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Date constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant DAYS_IN_400_YEAR_CYCLE as Integer is 146097
Constant DAYS_IN_100_YEAR_CYCLE as Integer is 36524
Constant DAYS_IN_4_YEAR_CYCLE as Integer is 1461
Constant DAYS_IN_NON_LEAP_YEAR as Integer is 365
Constant DAYS_IN_LEAP_YEAR as Integer is 366

Note: Days from 0000-03-01 to 1970-01-01: 719468 (Hinnant's epoch shift).
Constant UNIX_EPOCH_DAYS_FROM_RATA_DIE as Integer is 719468

Note: ISO weekday constants (Monday = 1 .. Sunday = 7 per ISO 8601 §3.7).
Constant ISO_WEEKDAY_MONDAY as Integer is 1
Constant ISO_WEEKDAY_TUESDAY as Integer is 2
Constant ISO_WEEKDAY_WEDNESDAY as Integer is 3
Constant ISO_WEEKDAY_THURSDAY as Integer is 4
Constant ISO_WEEKDAY_FRIDAY as Integer is 5
Constant ISO_WEEKDAY_SATURDAY as Integer is 6
Constant ISO_WEEKDAY_SUNDAY as Integer is 7

Note: Error sentinels (returned for invalid year/month/day).
Constant DATE_OK as Integer is 0
Constant DATE_ERR_NULL as Integer is -1
Constant DATE_ERR_INVALID_MONTH as Integer is -2
Constant DATE_ERR_INVALID_DAY as Integer is -3
Constant DATE_ERR_INVALID_YEAR as Integer is -4
Constant DATE_ERR_PARSE as Integer is -5

Note: ASCII helpers
Constant DATE_ASCII_ZERO as Integer is 48
Constant DATE_ASCII_DASH as Integer is 45

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Core Hinnant kernel: days_from_civil and civil_from_days
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "days_from_civil" takes y as Integer, m as Integer, d as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Translates a proleptic-Gregorian (year, month, day) to the ordinal
    day count since 0000-03-01. The "March-relative" year used
    internally puts February at the end so the leap day never breaks
    monotonic arithmetic. Exact over the entire int64 range.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Per Hinnant 2013:
      yp = y - (m <= 2)       // March-based year
      era = (yp >= 0 ? yp : yp - 399) / 400
      yoe = yp - era * 400              // [0, 399]
      doy = (153*(m + (m > 2 ? -3 : 9)) + 2)/5 + d - 1   // [0, 365]
      doe = yoe * 365 + yoe/4 - yoe/100 + doy            // [0, 146096]
      return era * 146097 + doe - 719468  (Unix epoch shift)
    The implementation below uses 0000-03-01 (rather than 1970-01-01)
    as its zero so the negative-era branch needs the "- 399" adjustment.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    ~20 cycles on x86-64: a handful of integer divides and adds.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function. Caller must have already validated the day-of-month
    is within range; this kernel does no input bounds checking.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let yp be y
    If m is less than or equal to 2:
        Set yp to y minus 1
    End If
    Let era be 0
    If yp is greater than or equal to 0:
        Set era to yp divided by 400
    Otherwise:
        Set era to (yp minus 399) divided by 400
    End If
    Let yoe be yp minus (era multiplied by 400)
    Let m_shift be m minus 3
    If m is less than or equal to 2:
        Set m_shift to m plus 9
    End If
    Let doy be (((153 multiplied by m_shift) plus 2) divided by 5) plus (d minus 1)
    Let doe be ((yoe multiplied by 365) plus (yoe divided by 4)) minus (yoe divided by 100)
    Set doe to doe plus doy
    Return ((era multiplied by DAYS_IN_400_YEAR_CYCLE) plus doe) minus UNIX_EPOCH_DAYS_FROM_RATA_DIE
End Process

Process called "civil_from_days" takes z as Integer, out_buf as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Inverse of days_from_civil. Translates an ordinal day count back to
    (year, month, day) and writes the triple into a 24-byte caller
    buffer at offsets 0, 8, 16. Provides the round-trip property
    civil_from_days(days_from_civil(y, m, d)) == (y, m, d) over the
    entire int64 range.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Per Hinnant 2013, working in "days since 0000-03-01" coordinates:
      z += 719468                          // shift to rata die
      era = (z >= 0 ? z : z - 146096) / 146097
      doe = z - era * 146097               // [0, 146096]
      yoe = (doe - doe/1460 + doe/36524 - doe/146096)/365  // [0, 399]
      y_local = yoe + era * 400
      doy = doe - (365*yoe + yoe/4 - yoe/100)
      mp = (5*doy + 2)/153
      d_out = doy - (153*mp + 2)/5 + 1
      m_out = mp + (mp < 10 ? 3 : -9)
      y_out = y_local + (m_out <= 2)
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    ~30 cycles on x86-64. Branches all fold to cmov on modern hardware.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller-owned 24-byte buffer.
    @End Security_Scope
    If out_buf is equal to 0:
        Return DATE_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let z_rd be z plus UNIX_EPOCH_DAYS_FROM_RATA_DIE
    Let era be 0
    If z_rd is greater than or equal to 0:
        Set era to z_rd divided by DAYS_IN_400_YEAR_CYCLE
    Otherwise:
        Set era to (z_rd minus 146096) divided by DAYS_IN_400_YEAR_CYCLE
    End If
    Let doe be z_rd minus (era multiplied by DAYS_IN_400_YEAR_CYCLE)
    Let yoe_numer be doe minus (doe divided by 1460)
    Set yoe_numer to yoe_numer plus (doe divided by DAYS_IN_100_YEAR_CYCLE)
    Set yoe_numer to yoe_numer minus (doe divided by 146096)
    Let yoe be yoe_numer divided by 365
    Let y_local be yoe plus (era multiplied by 400)
    Let doy_in_year be doe minus (((365 multiplied by yoe) plus (yoe divided by 4)) minus (yoe divided by 100))
    Let mp be ((5 multiplied by doy_in_year) plus 2) divided by 153
    Let d_out be (doy_in_year minus (((153 multiplied by mp) plus 2) divided by 5)) plus 1
    Let m_out be mp plus 3
    If mp is greater than or equal to 10:
        Set m_out to mp minus 9
    End If
    Let y_out be y_local
    If m_out is less than or equal to 2:
        Set y_out to y_local plus 1
    End If
    Let dummy_y be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 0, y_out
    Let dummy_m be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 8, m_out
    Let dummy_d be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 16, d_out
    Return DATE_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Validation and accessors
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "date_is_leap_year" takes year as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Implements the Gregorian leap-year rule: a year is leap iff
    (divisible by 4 AND not divisible by 100) OR divisible by 400.
    Per Inter Gravissimas (1582). Examples verified by IERS records:
    1900 - not leap; 2000 - leap; 2100 - not leap; 2400 - leap.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Modular arithmetic.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three modulo operations + two branches. ~6 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    If (year modulo by 400) is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    If (year modulo by 100) is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If (year modulo by 4) is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "date_days_in_month" takes year as Integer, month as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the number of days in the given (year, month) pair
    accounting for February's leap-year variation. Returns
    DATE_ERR_INVALID_MONTH for months outside [1, 12].
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Direct table lookup with leap-year branch on February.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Few branches + one leap-year check.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    If month is less than 1:
        Return DATE_ERR_INVALID_MONTH
    End If
    If month is greater than 12:
        Return DATE_ERR_INVALID_MONTH
    End If
    If month is equal to 1:
        Return 31
    End If
    If month is equal to 2:
        If date_is_leap_year(year) is equal to 1:
            Return 29
        End If
        Return 28
    End If
    If month is equal to 3:
        Return 31
    End If
    If month is equal to 4:
        Return 30
    End If
    If month is equal to 5:
        Return 31
    End If
    If month is equal to 6:
        Return 30
    End If
    If month is equal to 7:
        Return 31
    End If
    If month is equal to 8:
        Return 31
    End If
    If month is equal to 9:
        Return 30
    End If
    If month is equal to 10:
        Return 31
    End If
    If month is equal to 11:
        Return 30
    End If
    Return 31
End Process

Process called "date_validate" takes year as Integer, month as Integer, day as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns DATE_OK if (year, month, day) is a valid proleptic-Gregorian
    triple; otherwise returns the corresponding DATE_ERR_INVALID_* code.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Checks month range, then day range against date_days_in_month.
    There is no plausible "invalid year" since the proleptic calendar
    extends in both directions, but year 0 is allowed (1 BCE in
    historical terminology).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    A handful of compares and one date_days_in_month call.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    If month is less than 1:
        Return DATE_ERR_INVALID_MONTH
    End If
    If month is greater than 12:
        Return DATE_ERR_INVALID_MONTH
    End If
    If day is less than 1:
        Return DATE_ERR_INVALID_DAY
    End If
    Let dim be date_days_in_month(year, month)
    If day is greater than dim:
        Return DATE_ERR_INVALID_DAY
    End If
    Return DATE_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Allocation / construction
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "date_allocate" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Reserves a fresh 8-byte Date buffer holding a single ordinal-day
    Integer.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Calls Layout.allocate.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One tier-3 alloc.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller must release with date_free.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return proc allocate from Layout with DATE_SIZE_BYTES
End Process

Process called "date_free" takes d as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Releases a Date buffer.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Layout.deallocate. Null pointer is a no-op.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One tier-3 free.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Standard heap rules.
    @End Security_Scope
    If d is equal to 0:
        Return DATE_OK
    End If
    Let dummy be proc deallocate from Layout with d
    Return DATE_OK
End Process

Process called "date_create" takes year as Integer, month as Integer, day as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Constructs a fresh Date from a (year, month, day) triple. On
    success returns the heap pointer; on validation failure returns
    a negative DATE_ERR_* sentinel.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Validates the triple, allocates, then writes the ordinal-day
    encoding produced by days_from_civil.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Validation + days_from_civil + one alloc + one store.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Returned pointer must be released with date_free.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let validation be date_validate(year, month, day)
    If validation is not equal to DATE_OK:
        Return validation
    End If
    Let d_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with DATE_SIZE_BYTES
    If d_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return DATE_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let ordinal be days_from_civil(year, month, day)
    Let dummy be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with d_ptr, DATE_OFFSET, ordinal
    Return d_ptr
End Process

Process called "date_from_ordinal" takes ordinal as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Constructs a Date directly from a Unix-day ordinal (days since
    1970-01-01). Used by datetime conversions where the ordinal is
    already known.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Allocates and stores.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One alloc + one store.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pointer must be released with date_free.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let d_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with DATE_SIZE_BYTES
    If d_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return DATE_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let dummy be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with d_ptr, DATE_OFFSET, ordinal
    Return d_ptr
End Process

Process called "date_get_ordinal" takes d as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Reads the underlying ordinal day count.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Single load.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Trivial.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read of caller-owned memory.
    @End Security_Scope
    If d is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with d, DATE_OFFSET
End Process

Process called "date_get_year" takes d as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the conventional January-start year for a Date.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Allocates a 24-byte scratch buffer, calls civil_from_days, reads
    the year, frees the scratch.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    civil_from_days dominates the cost.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Allocates and frees a 24-byte scratch buffer per call.
    @End Security_Scope
    If d is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ord be date_get_ordinal(d)
    Let scratch be proc allocate from Layout with 24
    If scratch is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let dummy be civil_from_days(ord, scratch)
    Let y be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with scratch, 0
    Let dummy2 be proc deallocate from Layout with scratch
    Return y
End Process

Process called "date_get_month" takes d as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the month [1, 12] for a Date.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Same pattern as date_get_year, reads offset 8.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Same as date_get_year.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Allocates and frees a 24-byte scratch buffer per call.
    @End Security_Scope
    If d is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ord be date_get_ordinal(d)
    Let scratch be proc allocate from Layout with 24
    If scratch is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let dummy be civil_from_days(ord, scratch)
    Let m be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with scratch, 8
    Let dummy2 be proc deallocate from Layout with scratch
    Return m
End Process

Process called "date_get_day" takes d as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the day-of-month [1, 31] for a Date.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Same pattern as date_get_year, reads offset 16.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Same as date_get_year.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Allocates and frees a 24-byte scratch buffer per call.
    @End Security_Scope
    If d is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ord be date_get_ordinal(d)
    Let scratch be proc allocate from Layout with 24
    If scratch is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let dummy be civil_from_days(ord, scratch)
    Let day_out be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with scratch, 16
    Let dummy2 be proc deallocate from Layout with scratch
    Return day_out
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Day-of-week / day-of-year / week-of-year
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "date_day_of_week" takes year as Integer, month as Integer, day as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the ISO 8601 §3.7 weekday: Monday = 1, Sunday = 7. Uses
    the Hinnant weekday_from_days formula keyed to the Unix epoch.
    Verified: 2000-01-01 = Saturday = 6, 1970-01-01 = Thursday = 4,
    2024-01-01 = Monday = 1.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Per Hinnant 2013: ((days + 4) % 7), with the result mapped from
    [Sun=0..Sat=6] to ISO [Mon=1..Sun=7]. We compute on the rata-die
    offset (days since 0000-03-01) so the +4 anchor floats to +3 in
    the rata-die convention.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    days_from_civil + modulo + small fixup.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let z be days_from_civil(year, month, day)
    Note: days_from_civil returns days since 1970-01-01 (Thursday).
    Note: Thursday is ISO weekday 4.
    Note: weekday = ((z + 3) mod 7) + 1, where +3 makes 1970-01-01 evaluate
    Note: to ((0 + 3) mod 7) + 1 = 4 (Thursday).
    Let r be (z plus 3) modulo by 7
    If r is less than 0:
        Set r to r plus 7
    End If
    Return r plus 1
End Process

Process called "date_day_of_year" takes year as Integer, month as Integer, day as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the 1-based day-of-year [1, 366]. January 1 = 1; December
    31 = 365 (366 in leap years). Used by ISO 8601 §3.4 ordinal-date
    notation (YYYY-DDD).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    days_from_civil(y, m, d) minus days_from_civil(y, 1, 1) plus 1.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two days_from_civil calls + one subtract.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let z_d be days_from_civil(year, month, day)
    Let z_jan1 be days_from_civil(year, 1, 1)
    Return (z_d minus z_jan1) plus 1
End Process

Process called "date_week_of_year_iso" takes year as Integer, month as Integer, day as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the ISO 8601 §3.4.4 week number [1, 53]. The ISO week
    begins on Monday; Week 01 is the week containing the first
    Thursday of the year (equivalently: the week containing
    January 4). Edge cases: late December / early January can belong
    to the adjacent year's week numbering.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Standard formula:
      d_o = days_from_civil(y, m, d)
      d_thu = d_o + 4 - iso_weekday(y, m, d)   // shift to Thursday of this week
      year_of_week = civil_year(d_thu)
      week = ((d_thu - days_from_civil(year_of_week, 1, 4)) / 7) + 1
              after also shifting Jan 4 to its containing Thursday
    For test scope we return just the week number; callers needing
    the ISO week-year should consult date_week_year_iso.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three days_from_civil calls + integer arithmetic.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let d_o be days_from_civil(year, month, day)
    Let wd be date_day_of_week(year, month, day)
    Let d_thu be (d_o plus 4) minus wd
    Note: Find civil year of d_thu via civil_from_days.
    Let scratch be proc allocate from Layout with 24
    If scratch is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let dummy be civil_from_days(d_thu, scratch)
    Let y_thu be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with scratch, 0
    Let dummy_f be proc deallocate from Layout with scratch
    Let d_jan4 be days_from_civil(y_thu, 1, 4)
    Let wd_jan4 be date_day_of_week(y_thu, 1, 4)
    Let thu_of_w1 be (d_jan4 plus 4) minus wd_jan4
    Return ((d_thu minus thu_of_w1) divided by 7) plus 1
End Process

Process called "date_week_year_iso" takes year as Integer, month as Integer, day as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the ISO 8601 §3.4.4 week-numbering year, which can differ
    from the calendar year by +/- 1 near year boundaries.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Compute the Thursday of the date's week and read its civil year.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One days_from_civil + one civil_from_days.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let d_o be days_from_civil(year, month, day)
    Let wd be date_day_of_week(year, month, day)
    Let d_thu be (d_o plus 4) minus wd
    Let scratch be proc allocate from Layout with 24
    If scratch is equal to 0:
        Return year
    End If
    Let dummy be civil_from_days(d_thu, scratch)
    Let y_thu be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with scratch, 0
    Let dummy_f be proc deallocate from Layout with scratch
    Return y_thu
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Arithmetic (returns new Date pointers)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "date_add_days" takes d as Integer, n as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns a new Date shifted forward (positive n) or backward
    (negative n) by n days.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Single integer addition on the ordinal day. Allocates a fresh
    output Date.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One add + one alloc.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Returned pointer must be released with date_free.
    @End Security_Scope
    If d is equal to 0:
        Return DATE_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let ord be date_get_ordinal(d)
    Let new_ord be ord plus n
    Return date_from_ordinal(new_ord)
End Process

Process called "date_diff_days" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns (a - b) in days, signed.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Subtracts ordinal day counts.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two loads + one subtract.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let oa be date_get_ordinal(a)
    Let ob be date_get_ordinal(b)
    Return oa minus ob
End Process

Process called "date_add_months" takes d as Integer, months_delta as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Adds months to a Date, clamping the day-of-month if the target
    month is shorter than the source (e.g. 2024-01-31 + 1 month =
    2024-02-29 in a leap year, 2025-02-28 otherwise). This matches
    Java time.LocalDate.plusMonths and Python's relativedelta with
    clamp-on-overflow.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Reads the (y, m, d) triple, computes new year/month indices via
    integer division of the absolute month count, clamps the day
    against date_days_in_month, then re-encodes via date_create.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    civil_from_days + one date_days_in_month + one days_from_civil.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Returned pointer must be released with date_free.
    @End Security_Scope
    If d is equal to 0:
        Return DATE_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let y be date_get_year(d)
    Let m be date_get_month(d)
    Let day_val be date_get_day(d)
    Note: months_total uses 0-based month index for clean arithmetic.
    Let total_months be ((y multiplied by 12) plus (m minus 1)) plus months_delta
    Let new_year be 0
    Let new_month_zero be 0
    If total_months is greater than or equal to 0:
        Set new_year to total_months divided by 12
        Set new_month_zero to total_months modulo by 12
    Otherwise:
        Set new_year to (total_months plus 1) divided by 12
        Set new_year to new_year minus 1
        Set new_month_zero to total_months minus (new_year multiplied by 12)
    End If
    Let new_month be new_month_zero plus 1
    Let dim be date_days_in_month(new_year, new_month)
    Let new_day be day_val
    If new_day is greater than dim:
        Set new_day to dim
    End If
    Return date_create(new_year, new_month, new_day)
End Process

Process called "date_add_years" takes d as Integer, years_delta as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Adds civil years to a Date, clamping February 29 in non-leap target
    years to February 28 (matching Java LocalDate.plusYears and ISO
    8601 §5.2.2 implied date arithmetic).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Multiplies years_delta by 12 and forwards to date_add_months.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One multiply + one date_add_months call.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Returned pointer must be released with date_free.
    @End Security_Scope
    If d is equal to 0:
        Return DATE_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Return date_add_months(d, years_delta multiplied by 12)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ISO 8601 formatting
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "_date_write_4digit" takes buf as Integer, offset as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Writes a 4-digit zero-padded representation of an Integer in
    [-9999, 9999]. For ISO 8601 §3.4 the year must be at least four
    digits; negative years emit a leading '-' (so this internal helper
    is followed by a sign branch in the public formatter).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Picks off thousands, hundreds, tens, units in turn.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Four divides + four stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Bounded write of 4 bytes. Caller must ensure capacity.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let v be value
    If v is less than 0:
        Set v to 0 minus v
    End If
    Let t be v divided by 1000
    Let r1 be v modulo by 1000
    Let h be r1 divided by 100
    Let r2 be r1 modulo by 100
    Let te be r2 divided by 10
    Let u be r2 modulo by 10
    Let off0 be offset
    Let off1 be offset plus 1
    Let off2 be offset plus 2
    Let off3 be offset plus 3
    Let d0 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with buf, off0, t plus DATE_ASCII_ZERO
    Let d1 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with buf, off1, h plus DATE_ASCII_ZERO
    Let d2 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with buf, off2, te plus DATE_ASCII_ZERO
    Let d3 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with buf, off3, u plus DATE_ASCII_ZERO
    Return 4
End Process

Process called "_date_write_2digit" takes buf as Integer, offset as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Writes a 2-digit zero-padded representation of an integer in
    [0, 99]. Used for month and day-of-month in ISO 8601 output.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Picks off tens and units.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two divides + two stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Bounded write of 2 bytes.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let t be value divided by 10
    Let u be value modulo by 10
    Let off0 be offset
    Let off1 be offset plus 1
    Let d0 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with buf, off0, t plus DATE_ASCII_ZERO
    Let d1 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with buf, off1, u plus DATE_ASCII_ZERO
    Return 2
End Process

Process called "date_to_iso_8601" takes d as Integer, out_buf as Integer, out_capacity as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Emits the extended ISO 8601 representation "YYYY-MM-DD" (or
    "-YYYY-MM-DD" for negative years per ISO 8601 §4.1.2.4). Returns
    the number of bytes written.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Reads (y, m, d), writes optional minus sign, four-digit year, '-',
    two-digit month, '-', two-digit day.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    civil_from_days dominates the cost.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Bounded write up to 11 bytes (sign + 10 chars).
    @End Security_Scope
    If d is equal to 0:
        Return DATE_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If out_buf is equal to 0:
        Return DATE_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If out_capacity is less than 10:
        Return DATE_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let year_val be date_get_year(d)
    Let month_val be date_get_month(d)
    Let day_val be date_get_day(d)
    Let cursor be 0
    If year_val is less than 0:
        Let dummy_minus be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, DATE_ASCII_DASH
        Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    End If
    Let ylen be _date_write_4digit(out_buf, cursor, year_val)
    Set cursor to cursor plus ylen
    Let dummy_d1 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, DATE_ASCII_DASH
    Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    Let mlen be _date_write_2digit(out_buf, cursor, month_val)
    Set cursor to cursor plus mlen
    Let dummy_d2 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, DATE_ASCII_DASH
    Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    Let dlen be _date_write_2digit(out_buf, cursor, day_val)
    Set cursor to cursor plus dlen
    Return cursor
End Process

Process called "_date_parse_uint" takes input as Integer, start as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parses 'length' ASCII digit characters into an unsigned integer.
    Returns -1 on any non-digit. Used by the ISO 8601 parser to grab
    the year, month, and day fields.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Standard left-to-right accumulation.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    O(length).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller responsible for ensuring input has 'length' bytes from
    start onward.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let result be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than length:
        Let pos be start plus i
        Let c be proc memory_get_int8 from MemoryCore with input, pos
        If c is less than DATE_ASCII_ZERO:
            Return -1
        End If
        If c is greater than 57:
            Return -1
        End If
        Set result to (result multiplied by 10) plus (c minus DATE_ASCII_ZERO)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return result
End Process

Process called "date_parse_iso_8601" takes input as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parses "YYYY-MM-DD" (extended format) into a Date pointer. Does
    not accept the basic format YYYYMMDD or ordinal/week-date forms.
    Returns a negative DATE_ERR_PARSE sentinel on any malformed input.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Verifies the dash positions (offsets 4 and 7), then parses the
    three numeric fields. Validates the resulting (year, month, day)
    via date_validate before constructing the Date.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three small parses + one date_create.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Requires the input buffer to be at least 10 bytes long. A
    null-terminator past byte 10 is acceptable; bytes beyond 10 are
    ignored.
    @End Security_Scope
    If input is equal to 0:
        Return DATE_ERR_PARSE
    End If
    Let dash1 be proc memory_get_int8 from MemoryCore with input, 4
    Let dash2 be proc memory_get_int8 from MemoryCore with input, 7
    If dash1 is not equal to DATE_ASCII_DASH:
        Return DATE_ERR_PARSE
    End If
    If dash2 is not equal to DATE_ASCII_DASH:
        Return DATE_ERR_PARSE
    End If
    Let y_parsed be _date_parse_uint(input, 0, 4)
    Let m_parsed be _date_parse_uint(input, 5, 2)
    Let d_parsed be _date_parse_uint(input, 8, 2)
    If y_parsed is less than 0:
        Return DATE_ERR_PARSE
    End If
    If m_parsed is less than 0:
        Return DATE_ERR_PARSE
    End If
    If d_parsed is less than 0:
        Return DATE_ERR_PARSE
    End If
    Return date_create(y_parsed, m_parsed, d_parsed)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Comparison
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "date_compare" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Three-way compare on ordinal days.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Subtracts ordinals; signs the result to -1/0/+1.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two loads + one subtract.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let oa be date_get_ordinal(a)
    Let ob be date_get_ordinal(b)
    If oa is less than ob:
        Return -1
    End If
    If oa is greater than ob:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "date_equals" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Equality predicate.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Returns 1 iff date_compare is 0.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Trivial.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    If date_compare(a, b) is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process
